<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-higher-order-partial-derivatives">
  <title>Higher order partial derivatives</title>

  <objectives>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Differentiate partial derivatives again to study second-order behavior.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use Clairaut's theorem to identify when mixed partials agree.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Recognize how higher-order partials appear in fundamental equations of physics.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </objectives>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Second-order partial derivatives of <m>z=f(x,y)</m>:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>\pdv[2]{z}{x} \amp = f_{xx}(x,y)</mrow>
        <mrow>\pdv[2]{z}{y} \amp = f_{yy}(x,y)</mrow>
        <mrow>\pdv{z}{y}{x} \amp = f_{xy}(x,y)</mrow>
        <mrow>\pdv{z}{x}{y} \amp = f_{yx}(x,y)</mrow>
      </md>

      <p>
        Yes, the mixed partial notation is confusing.
        In differential notation, the operators are applied inside-out, while in function notation, the operators are applied left to right.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        <theorem>
          <title>Clairaut's Theorem</title>
          
          
          <statement>
            <p>
              If <m>f</m> is defined on a disk containing <m>(a,b)</m> and <m>f_{xy}</m> and <m>f_{yx}</m> are continuous in that disk, then
              <me>
                f_{xy}(a,b)=f_{yx}(a,b)
              </me>.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </theorem>
        
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Some partial differential equations:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Wave equation:
            </p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\pdv[2]{u}{t} \amp = a^{2}\pdv[2]{u}{x} </mrow>
              <mrow>\pdv[2]{u}{t} \amp = a^{2}\qty(\pdv[2]{u}{x}+\pdv[2]{u}{y}) </mrow>
            </md>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Heat equation:
            </p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\pdv{u}{t} \amp = a^{2}\pdv[2]{u}{x} </mrow>
              <mrow>\pdv{u}{t} \amp = a^{2}\qty(\pdv[2]{u}{x}+\pdv[2]{u}{y}) </mrow>
            </md>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Laplace's equation:
            </p>
            <md>
              <mrow> \pdv[2]{u}{x} + \pdv[2]{u}{y} \amp = 0 </mrow>
              <mrow> \pdv[2]{u}{x} + \pdv[2]{u}{y} + \pdv[2]{u}{z} \amp = 0 </mrow>
            </md>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Begin by recalling the single-variable Taylor expansion:
        <me>
          f(x) \approx f(a) + f'(a)(x-a) + \frac{1}{2} f''(a)(x-a)^{2}
        </me>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The tangent line is just the first-order approximation, and adding higher-order terms improves accuracy.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Connect to the previous section: The tangent plane
        <me>
          z \approx z_{0} + \pdv{f}{x}(x-x_{0}) + \pdv{f}{y}(y-y_{0})
        </me>
        is the first-order Taylor polynomial for <m>f(x,y)</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Introduce second-order terms using higher partial derivatives:
        <me>
          f(x,y) \approx f(x_{0},y_{0}) + \pdv{f}{x}(x-x_{0}) + \pdv{f}{y}(y-y_{0})
        </me>
        <me>
          \quad + \frac{1}{2} \pdv[2]{f}{x}(x-x_{0})^{2} + \pdv[2]{f}{x}{y}(x-x_{0})(y-y_{0}) + \frac{1}{2} \pdv[2]{f}{y}(y-y_{0})^{2}.
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Interpret each term:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              First-order terms describe tilt.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Pure second derivatives describe curvature in coordinate directions.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Mixed partials describe interaction between variables.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Emphasize symmetry of mixed partials when conditions allow (Clairaut's theorem).
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Provide a worked example:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Compute first and second partial derivatives at a point.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Write the quadratic Taylor approximation.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Use it to estimate a nearby value.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Compare to the actual value.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Geometric meaning:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              First-order: tangent plane.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Second-order: quadratic surface approximating curvature.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              The quadratic form determines local shape.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        General multivariable Taylor expansion:
        <me>
          f(x,y) = \sum_{k=0}^{n}\text{(all $k$th-order partial terms in $(x-x_{0}),(y-y_{0})$)}+ R_{n},\text{,}
        </me>
        where each term involves partial derivatives of total order <m>k</m> evaluated at <m>(x_{0},y_{0})</m>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Each degree <m>k</m> term consists of all products
        <me>
          (x-x_{0})^{i} (y-y_{0})^{j}
        </me>
        with <m>i+j=k</m>, multiplied by the corresponding partial derivative
        <me>
          \frac{\partial^{k}f}{\partial x^{i}\partial y^{j}}(x_{0},y_{0}).
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        The approximation improves as higher-order terms are included.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
